{"_id":"aXF2Adq2YDqj8F14","name":"Everything Shields Guide","content":"<h2><strong>Thank you for using the Everything Shields foundry module!</strong></h2>\n<p>Most of the things you'll find in the Everything Shields compendia should be self-explanatory, but there are some custom-crafted processes that come packaged with this module that may require a bit of explaning. Some or all of these processes can be disabled if desired through the module settings menu.</p>\n<h4><strong>Runes </strong></h4>\n<p>Because the Foundry system and the Pathfinder Second Edition system within it do not have direct support for applying runes to shields, we have created a custom system that will allow you to combine runes with your shields to have all of the important values calculated automatically for you.</p>\n<p>When you drop a shield rune onto a character sheet that has a shield in its inventory, you will be asked if you would like to etch that rune onto one of the shields. You should see a dialog box that allows you to choose which shield you would like to apply it to, or if you would prefer to simply send that rune to your inventory.</p>\n<p>If you do not have a shield in the character's inventory, the rune will go straight into the inventory.  You may also drag and drop runes from your inventory back into your inventory to receive this prompt again.</p>\n<p>When you apply a Shield Potency Rune to a shield, its Hit Point total and current Hit Point value will be set to the new value. The Price, Level, and Name of the shield will be updated to reflect the total Price (base shield Price + Shield Potency Rune Price) and the highest Level of the shield. If the added rune is higher than the level of the base shield (and higher than the level of any other runes or precious materials on the shield), then the shield's Level will be set to the same Level as the new rune. The Description of the shield will be updated to include a button that allows you to remove the Shield Potency Rune from your shield and place it back into your inventory. The Name will be generated based on the standard naming pattern for weapons and armor laid out in the Pathfinder Second Edition Core Rulebook.  For example, a hoplon that has a +2 Shield Potency Rune, a Hardened Rune, Greater, and a Seeing rune etched onto it will be named \"+2 Greater Hardened Seeing Hoplon.\"</p>\n<p>When you apply a Hardened Rune to a shield, its hardness will be set to the new value, automatically calculated based on the weight category of the shield (light, medium, or heavy). Its Price, Level, Description, and Name will be updated in the same way as it is for a Shield Potency Rune.</p>\n<p>When you apply a property rune to a shield, the system will first check if there is a Shield Potency Rune, and whether you are able to apply another property rune based on how many property runes the shield already has and what the current level its Shield Potency Rune is. If there is space on the shield for the new property rune, the shield's Price, Level, and Name will but updated just like the Shield Potency Rune, but the Description will be updated to include the Description of the new property rune, along with a specific button to remove that property rune.  If the property rune has rule elements and rule element selections, those will be copied onto the shield and will function once the shield is equipped and invested.</p>\n<p>If you do not wish to use our automations and have disabled them, you may still gain the rule element automations applied to some of our property runes by investing those runes individually.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h4><strong>Precious Materials</strong></h4>\n<p>We have added the ability to automatically calculate your shield's Hit Points, Hardness, Level, Name, and Price based on precious material settings.  To do this, simply navigate to the details tab of the shield you would like to change, and select an option from the Precious Material and Precious Material Grade dropdowns.  You must select a value for both of these fields before any changes will be calculated.  The changes will be calculated as outlined in the Everything Shields PDF, page 15.</p>\n<p>Please note that the dropdowns in the Pathfinder Second Edition Foundry system allow you to make some selections that do not exist, for example you could choose \"Adamantine\" as your Precious Material, and then choose \"Low-Grade\" as the material grade.  There are no statistics given for Low-Grade Adamantine in the Pathfinder Second Edition Core Rulebook, so it is assumed that this material is not possible to create or craft with.  Therefore if you select a combination that does not exist in the Core Rulebook, no changes will be made to the shield.</p>\n<p>Precious Material adjustments will be calculated in tandem with shield fundamental runes as outlined in the Everything Shields PDF, page 15.</p>\n<p>We do not recommend using the pre-made precious material shields that are in the Pathfinder Second Edition Foundry system. Even though these shields will work with our module, the names get a little skewed. It is more reliable to start with a regular shield of that type (e.g. Steel Shield) and then navigate to the details tab and set the precious materials there. Our module will update the name for you based on your selection.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h4><strong>Specific Magic Shields</strong></h4>\n<p>You may combine shield fundamental runes with specific magic shields, but you cannot combine property runes with them. You cannot combine any runes from Everything Shields with Sturdy Shields or Wovenwood Shields.</p>\n<p>Some specific magic shields have base statistics that differ from their core shield type. For example the Forge Warden shield is classified as a steel shield, but it has Hardness 10 (instead of 5) and 40 Hit Points (instead of 20).  When applying a fundamental rune to a shield such as this, the difference between the specific magic shield's statistics and the statistics for a base shield of its type will be treated in the same way as precious materials and added onto the values after the fundamental runes have been calculated. See page 22 of the Everything Shields PDF for more details.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"rIqY5HUcAHArIcvJ":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.aXF2Adq2YDqj8F14"}},"schemaVersion":13}
